1 (2) Demonstrate financial need according to criteria established by the
2 Commission; and
3 (3) Attend one of the following institutions:
4 (i) The University of Maryland School of:
5 1. Medicine;
6 2. Dentistry;
7 3. Law;
8 4. Pharmacy; or
9 5. Social Work;
10 (ii) The University of Baltimore School of Law;
11 (iii) The Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine;
12 (iv) Virginia–Maryland Regional College of Veterinary Medicine;
13 (V) THE MERITUS SCHOOL OF OSTEOPATHIC MEDICINE;
14 [(v)] (VI) Any institution of higher education in the State offering a
15 master’s degree in nursing;
16 [(vi)] (VII) Any institution of higher education in the State offering a
17 master’s degree in social work; or
18 [(vii)] (VIII) Any institution of higher education in the State offering a
19 first professional degree in pharmacy.
20 (c) A graduate and professional scholarship award for a single school year may
21 not be less than $1,000 or more than $5,000.
22 (d) A recipient may not receive an award for longer than 8 semesters.
23 (e) (1) The Commission shall allocate grants for the Program to the
24 institutions of higher education specified in subsection (b)(3) of this section based on the
25 proportion of State residents enrolled in eligible programs at each institution.
26 (2) An institution of higher education that receives a grant under this
27 section shall provide the Commission with an annual audit describing the disposition of the
28 funds.

